{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17616726","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17616726"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:06:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:06:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16438"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16438","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16438"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.05,0.78,0,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9129"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67265"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9129","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9129"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16438"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52717"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4938"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5228"},{"type":"tags","id":"5229"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21685"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21687"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67265","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67265"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ENaloxone is commonly used in emergency departments in the treatment of opioid overdose.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pharmacological mechanism of action of naloxone?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Partial agonist at opioid receptors","Inverse agonist at opioid receptors","Competitive antagonist at opioid receptors","Allosteric modulator of opioid receptors","Non-competitive antagonist at opioid receptors"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENaloxone acts as a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecompetitive antagonist at opioid receptors\u003C/strong\u003E. It has high affinity for mu, kappa, and delta opioid receptors but no intrinsic activity. By competing with opioid agonists for receptor binding sites, it can rapidly reverse opioid effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options listed are incorrect, and are explained below:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-competitive antagonist at opioid receptors\u003C/strong\u003E - naloxone binds to the same site as opioid agonists and prevents their binding, therefore being classified as a competitive antagonist\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPartial agonist at opioid receptors\u003C/strong\u003E - naloxone has no intrinsic activity at opioid receptors\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInverse agonist at opioid receptors\u003C/strong\u003E - naloxone does not produce effects opposite to opioids, it simply blocks their actions\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAllosteric modulator of opioid receptors\u003C/strong\u003E - naloxone binds directly to the opioid binding site, not an allosteric site.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe competitive nature of naloxone\u0027s antagonism means its effects can be overcome by administering higher doses of opioids, though this is not recommended clinically. Its short duration of action (30-60 minutes) means patients may require repeated doses in cases of long-acting opioid overdose.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Naloxone is a competitive antagonist at mu, kappa, and delta opioid receptors.","Naloxone has high affinity for opioid receptors but no intrinsic activity, allowing it to displace opioid receptor agonists.","Naloxone has a short duration of action (30-60 minutes) due to rapid hepatic metabolism."],"references":["Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52717"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16438"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52717"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-04T11:15:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T11:16:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9129"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67265"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":